17:51.860 --> 17:56.660
Identity politics advocates for rights, equality, and justice for particular groups,

17:56.660 --> 18:00.180
such as women, people of color, and gay and trans people.

18:00.180 --> 18:04.340
This kind of activism presupposes that these group categories exist

18:04.340 --> 18:07.060
and are a useful basis for political organizing.

18:07.060 --> 18:09.460
Postmodernists do kind of the opposite.

18:09.460 --> 18:13.620
They want to show that these categories, race, gender, sexual orientation,

18:13.620 --> 18:18.100
are contingent social constructs and are themselves potentially oppressive.

18:18.100 --> 18:22.580
This is why conventional feminist activists often hate postmodern feminism.

18:22.580 --> 18:26.260
Because the postmodern feminists want to show that the whole concept of womanhood,

18:26.260 --> 18:29.460
for instance, is contingent and potentially oppressive,

18:29.460 --> 18:32.500
and they think we should be working to destabilize and undermine it.

18:32.500 --> 18:34.820
And then the conventional feminist activists say,

18:34.820 --> 18:39.540
the fuck, we need the concept of womanhood to organize around women's political interests.

18:39.540 --> 18:43.780
How are we supposed to do that if we undermine and destabilize the concept of womanhood?

18:43.780 --> 18:46.260
And in turn, the postmodern feminists say,

18:46.260 --> 18:51.140
well, here's a quotation from Judith Butler, the most famous postmodern feminist ever.

18:51.140 --> 18:56.020
Is it not a sign of despair over public politics when identity becomes its own policy,

18:56.020 --> 18:59.220
bringing with it those who would police it from various sides?

18:59.220 --> 19:02.500
And this is not a call to return to silence or invisibility,

19:02.500 --> 19:06.500
but rather to make use of a category that can be called into question,

19:06.500 --> 19:08.980
made to account for what it excludes.

19:08.980 --> 19:11.460
If you take the first part of that quote out of context,

19:11.460 --> 19:14.100
it almost sounds like something Jordan Peterson could have said.

19:14.100 --> 19:19.220
The difference is that JP actually does think we should return to silence and invisibility.

19:19.220 --> 19:20.180
Or does he?

19:20.180 --> 19:22.020
It's hard to tell what he thinks.

19:22.020 --> 19:23.220
More on that in a moment.

19:23.220 --> 19:25.540
I bring all of this up to show that one,

19:25.540 --> 19:31.860
the idea of postmodern neo-Marxist identity politics as a unifying concept of the left is nonsensical,

19:31.860 --> 19:36.980
and two, identity politics is not this dogma that must go unquestioned.

19:36.980 --> 19:41.060
There are sophisticated debates about this going on within leftist academia,

19:41.140 --> 19:44.500
but Jordan Peterson either doesn't know that or doesn't care.

19:44.500 --> 19:49.700
He uses the term postmodern neo-Marxism to characterize the left as a unified philosophical

19:49.700 --> 19:55.060
force bent on destroying Western civilization when in fact it's a bunch of bumbling buffoons

19:55.060 --> 19:58.580
who can't stop squabbling with each other over every goddamn little issue.

19:58.580 --> 20:03.460
The only reason I can think of that the left would appear to be a unified philosophical force

20:03.460 --> 20:08.260
is if you're so far to the right that literally everyone who supports the economic and social

20:08.260 --> 20:12.260
advancement of disadvantaged groups looks like one homogenous enemy.

20:12.260 --> 20:14.260
But is that what Jordan Peterson is saying?

20:14.260 --> 20:18.740
That he opposes all social progress for women, racial, and sexual minorities?

20:18.740 --> 20:23.380
Well it's difficult to say, because while he spends much of his time comparing activists

20:23.380 --> 20:28.340
for these movements to 20th century mass murderers, he resists being pinned down to

20:28.340 --> 20:30.020
any more specific position.

20:30.020 --> 20:32.580
I was maybe too harsh on Kathy Newman earlier.

20:32.580 --> 20:35.940
She came out of the interview looking bad, but she had a tough job to do.

20:35.940 --> 20:39.700
Peterson's rhetorical strategy involves saying something that's more or less

20:39.700 --> 20:44.500
uncontroversially true, while at the same time implying something controversial.

20:44.500 --> 20:48.740
For instance, Jordan Peterson will make a claim like there are biological differences

20:48.740 --> 20:51.300
between men and women, which is obviously true.

20:51.300 --> 20:55.140
But he'll say it in the context of a conversation about the underrepresentation

20:55.140 --> 20:59.300
of women in government, which implies… what exactly?

20:59.300 --> 21:00.820
So how do you respond to this?

21:00.820 --> 21:05.140
Well, either you fall into the trap of arguing against the obviously true statement,

21:05.140 --> 21:09.620
or you have to guess at what he's implying in response to which he can accuse you of

21:09.620 --> 21:13.940
misrepresenting him, which is exactly what happened with the Kathy Newman interview.

21:13.940 --> 21:18.420
The most famous moment where Peterson does this is the notorious lobster argument.

21:18.420 --> 21:19.620
So he starts by saying,

21:19.620 --> 21:25.620
There's this idea that hierarchical structures are a sociological construct

21:25.620 --> 21:27.220
of the Western patriarchy.

21:27.220 --> 21:30.340
And then he goes on to say that lobsters exist in hierarchies,

21:30.340 --> 21:34.020
and lobsters predate Western patriarchy by millions of years,

21:34.020 --> 21:36.900
so checkmate postmodern neo-Marxists.

21:36.900 --> 21:41.940
You're saying that we should organize our societies along the lines of the lobsters?

21:41.940 --> 21:45.700
I'm saying that it's inevitable that there will be continuity in the way that animals

21:45.700 --> 21:48.340
and human beings organize their structures.

21:48.340 --> 21:51.700
The problem with that is that no one has ever said

21:51.700 --> 21:55.700
that every hierarchy is the product of Western patriarchy.

21:55.700 --> 22:00.020
This is such a massive straw man that it overshadows any uncharitable interpretation

22:00.020 --> 22:03.140
of Peterson suggested by Kathy Newman in this interview.

22:03.140 --> 22:07.220
No one on the left denies that there are some natural hierarchies.

22:07.220 --> 22:10.900
Even the anarchists whose whole thing is abolishing hierarchies

22:10.900 --> 22:14.500
limit themselves to the abolition of unjust hierarchies.

22:14.500 --> 22:17.060
No one wants to abolish lobster hierarchies.

22:17.060 --> 22:22.820
The hierarchies we're interested in are those of gender, race, and economics within our own society,

22:22.820 --> 22:25.700
to which the lobster case is a complete non-sequitur.

22:25.700 --> 22:29.540
I mean, you could use Peterson's lobster argument the same way he uses it

22:29.540 --> 22:32.660
to justify literally any hierarchy or authority,

22:32.660 --> 22:34.180
no matter how unjust.

22:34.180 --> 22:38.100
You could be an 18th century Republican arguing against the monarchy,

22:38.100 --> 22:40.260
and the monarch could turn around and say,

22:40.260 --> 22:42.500
well, hierarchies are inevitable.

22:42.500 --> 22:43.940
God save the lobster queen.

22:45.940 --> 22:47.060
